Real estate market update with the January data 🔎 A bit of insight…

November-January are historically slower months for Seattle real estate. This time around it was further exacerbated by higher interest rates, tech layoffs, and inflation/economy chatter. The January data reflects this!

Fast forward to today, we are seeing an increase in buyer activity which has resulted in the return of competition and multiple offer situations in some cases. (Totally depends on the home, it’s location, condition, etc…) This is expected to continue and even increase as we enter what is typically a busy spring market here in Seattle!

Many sellers are prepping their homes for the market behind the scenes. We should see an increase in inventory but it’s unlikely to reach balanced levels (around 3-6 months) for multiple reasons. Demand is strong and many sellers don’t want to sell and lose the low interest rates they secured from purchasing or refinancing in 2020-21.

The average 30yr mortgage fixed interest rate is 6.6% as of today, 2/13/23.

If you have any questions at all about the market in your area and/or you have a real estate need I can help with, please don’t hesitate to reach out! 💬

A quick Market Monday update with the latest Seattle/Eastside stats from February. 🔎🏠 If you’re interested in a different area - let me know!! Some key takeaways…

- Despite what headlines say (which are delayed and don’t share the full story…) the housing market in Seattle is strong. We’re seeing stable demand, low supply, and an increase in prices and competition (although it’s nothing at all like 2021 or early 2022).

- So far seasonal trends are holding. If this continues, median home prices should continue to rise through the spring before peaking around May/June and then declining in the back half of the year.

- The dramatic rise in interest rates that we’ve seen in the past year (and the corresponding drop in the number of buyers who can afford homes) have so far failed to break the market out of its usual seasonal patterns and instead just made the cool-down that always happens in the back half of the year much larger than usual in late 2022.

- As of today (3/13) the average interest rate for a 30yr fixed mortgage is about 6.57%. Experts predict rates to drop later on in the year.

Here’s a snapshot of the real estate market in Seattle, with data from March 2023! (If you’re interested in a different area within Washington, send me a DM and I’ll get you the stats. 😊)

We’re currently facing low inventory and therefore fewer sales overall. Every day we are feeling an increase in buyer competition (especially over the most desirable listings) as the spring market heats up!

Interest rates remain higher than what we’re used to seeing in the last few years, so many homeowners don’t want to sell and compromise their record-low rate. They’re staying put and this is contributing to the lack of inventory.

Prices have jumped 11% from the start of 2023 until now. Our market remains stable as the demand is solid and growing. It’s important to take the headlines you read with a grain of salt, as they don’t tell the full story!

As always, DM me with any questions. 🤎

Happy Market Monday 🧡🏡👩🏼‍💻 here’s a look at the real estate market in Seattle, with data from April. As always, if you’re interested in a different area within Washington, send me a DM and I’ll get you the stats!

We are still seeing low inventory, high buyer demand, and multiple offer situations over the most desirable homes. This is in line with the seller-favored market we typically see in our spring market, however it’s less dramatic than in recent years.

Seattle’s median home price is up 10.2% from January!! Our market is stable. 42% of houses that closed in March/April escalated at least 1% above their list price (3.7% went 20% or more over list, and 9.2% went 10-20% over list). Additionally, 15.3% of condos and 12.9% of townhomes escalated by 1% or more in the same period (for resale townhomes the number was 20.6%, vs. 7.8% for new construction). 

Interest rates remain higher than what we’re used to seeing in the last few years, so many homeowners don’t want to sell and compromise their record-low rate. They’re staying put and this is contributing to the lack of inventory.

A look at the Seattle housing market with stats as of June 1 🤎 (If you’d like the data for a specific Seattle neighborhood or a completely different city in WA, let me know!) May followed similar trends as April. The bottom line — our local market remains stable despite the doom you see in the (click-bait) headlines.

Inventory remains low all things considered, which increases competition amongst the buyers out there. 40% of Seattle single family homes homes sold above list price in May. These homes sold for a median of 7% over the list price.

We did see an uptick in the median sold price of $905K (which is up 12% already from January 2023). This could be the peak for the year, as historically in our area prices tend to fall through the summer before peaking again in the fall.

Higher interest rates are still preventing many buyers from starting their search and many sellers from selling. When rates drop it’s likely that we’ll see more buyers and therefore more bidding wars and price escalations, which may counteract the attractive lower rate. 

Curious about what it would look like for you personally to buy or sell in the current market? Send me a DM & let’s chat!! 😊

CLOSED! Huge congratulations to my wonderful clients @jenny_masterson_ + Trevor who just got the keys to this beautiful home 🗝🥂 I couldn’t be happier for them and had so much fun guiding them through the process!

Jenny & Trevor reached out after seeing an Instagram post I shared about the info packets I give my buyers. These packets include my home buying guide, a buyer wishlist worksheet, a sample MLS listing, market stats for their area(s) of interest, a Starbucks gift card, and more. I sent them one in the mail and shortly after they received it we set up an initial Zoom call to chat further. We then had additional calls to go through the buying process step-by-step (including a sample purchase and sale agreement). This education piece is a big part of my process with all first-time buyers!

They worked quickly to get pre-approved for a mortgage and the house hunt began. This home was actually the very FIRST one we ever toured together!!! They seemed to know right away that it was the one. It doesn’t always happen this fast, but it’s so great (for all involved) when it does. We put together an incredibly competitive offer and out of the EIGHT OFFERS the sellers received, ours was the most attractive. 👏🏼

(DM me if you’re interested in seeing the data for a different local city!) The median price rose from $905,000 to $930,000 from just May to June. Despite higher rates, we are still seeing the most desirable houses in escalate notably (but not to the crazy levels we saw in 2021-22). This has bumped prices up 15.7% year to date, which is a solid amount of appreciation given the current rate environment.

That being said, if we go off of the historically strong seasonal trends for our area, prices are likely to fall slightly over the next couple months, tick back up in the fall, and dip around the holidays. We’ll see what happens with interest rates, as many buyers are waiting to start their search until the rates drop a little. (Although some are jumping in now due to the news that rates may actually rise in the 4th quarter…)

Seattle real estate stats from July are out!! 🤎

Slight dip in median closed price ($899,000 for single family homes/townhomes), which is common for our area this time of year! After a hot spring, summer tends to be slower before things pick up again in the fall.

This rate is pricing out buyers and keeping some sellers from wanting to sell and give up their incredible rates (many below 3% 😅). A major concern many have is that when rates come down, many buyers will jump in from the sidelines, resulting in crazy competition and price escalations. Based on what I’ve personally seen and heard in our industry, I have to agree with this! “Waiting for the rate to come down” might not make the most sense…

Market Monday update with Seattle real estate stats from September 🤎

Median price rose 3% from August to September AND is up 3% YOY. Right in line with the typical season trends we see in our area!!

About 1/3 of homes are selling above list price, and about 2/3 are selling in 15 days or less.

Inventory is up slightly, but still low all things considered.

The homes that are priced right & presented well are selling quickly in most cases. In some circumstances we’re seeing multiple offers and price escalations, however buyers have a lot more leverage in general right now than they’ve had in the last few years. There are more price reductions, more seller credits given to help the buyer down their interest rate and/or pay for closing costs, and more buyers contractual contingencies are staying in place.

This market is an interesting one and it means something different for everyone!! It’s arguably more important than ever to connect with an agent and lender ahead of time to get clear on your goals, and to figure out how you can make the current environment work for you. 🏡

Happy market Monday 🤍 here’s a snapshot of what’s happening with Seattle real estate with data from October…

Median price ticked down slightly from the month prior, and is down 5% from 2022. We tend to see this price dip in the back half of the year, so this is nothing new!!

The top section of the residential market is still selling quickly (over 1/3 of homes sold above list price and over 2/3 sold in 15 days or less). New construction + less desirable listings are seeing more price drops and room for buyer negotiation.

Inventory is still low all things considered! 1.8 months’ supply, giving sellers a bit of a leg up in most cases. A balanced market is closer to 3 months’ supply. Many homeowners are sitting on an interest rate at or below 3%, keeping them from wanting to sell.

In the real estate market, both buyers and sellers commonly initiate their processes in January. Buyers can enter the market as soon as they find a property, while sellers often take two to six months to prepare their homes for sale. As a result, the early part of the calendar year typically sees an increase in multiple offers, likely driven by sellers listing their properties in the spring, an influx of motivated buyers, and seasonal market trends. Historically, prices in our area tick up from January until peaking around May — this is expected to be the case in 2024 unless interest rates rise significantly.

Seattle real estate stats from November ✨

This time of year we always see a dip in new listings, overall activity, and sales. This year was no different, however we saw prices increase almost 5% from October (that seasonal fall bump)! Will be interesting to see what happens with prices this month. In the new year, it’s likely that prices will generally tick up from January through May/June when they usually peak in our area.

Interest rates remain high compared to prior years, but have come down a bit and are expected to drop a few times in 2024. It’s predicted that this will result in many more buyers entering the market and competing for homes.

Desirable homes are still selling above list price and fairly quickly, whereas new construction homes or less desirable ones are seeing more market time, price drops, and seller concessions for buyers.
